  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Oriskany Falls got its name from the word ORISKA, meaning the place or stream of nettles.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.oriskany.gov/history"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The village sits in a steep, narrow valley defined by three hills, with the Mohawk River dropping 45 feet in less than a mile.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4,
        23
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2",
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://nyfalls.com/waterfalls/oriskany-falls/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "By 1878 the Erie Canal was closed and the railroad became the main transportation line through the valley.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://nyfalls.com/waterfalls/oriskany-falls/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Oriskany Falls once hosted a bustling textile industry, with mills, foundries, and a distillery that served the growing community.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://nyfalls.com/waterfalls/oriskany-falls/"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The area’s early settlers were German Palatines granted land under the Burnetsfield Patent in 1723, making it the westernmost European settlement in New York at the time.",
